# Store Configuration

## Use configureStore

Always configure the store using `configureStore`.

```typescript
import { configureStore } from "@reduxjs/toolkit";
import authReducer from "@/features/auth/authSlice";

export const store = configureStore({
  reducer: {
    auth: authReducer,
  },
});
```

## Export Typed Types

Always export store types.

```typescript
export type RootState = ReturnType<typeof store.getState>;
export type AppDispatch = typeof store.dispatch;
```

---

# Typed Hooks

Create reusable typed hooks.

```typescript
import { useDispatch, useSelector } from "react-redux";
import type { AppDispatch, RootState } from "./store";

export const useAppDispatch = useDispatch.withTypes<AppDispatch>();

export const useAppSelector = useSelector.withTypes<RootState>();
```

Never use:

```typescript
useDispatch();
useSelector();
```

Use:

```typescript
useAppDispatch();
useAppSelector();
```

---

# Slice Design

## Single Responsibility

A slice should manage one domain.

Good:

```text
authSlice
usersSlice
notificationsSlice
```

Bad:

```text
appSlice
globalSlice
miscSlice
```

---

## Keep State Flat

Prefer normalized state.

Good:

```typescript
{
  entities: {
    "1": { id: "1", name: "John" }
  },
  ids: ["1"]
}
```

Bad:

```typescript
{
  users: [
    {
      id: "1",
      profile: {
        settings: {
          ...
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

---

## Use createEntityAdapter

For collections, use `createEntityAdapter`.

```typescript
import { createEntityAdapter, createSlice } from "@reduxjs/toolkit";

const usersAdapter = createEntityAdapter<User>();

const initialState = usersAdapter.getInitialState();
```

Benefits:

- Normalized state
- Efficient lookups
- Built-in selectors
- Easier updates

---

# Actions

## Use Slice Actions

Always use actions generated by `createSlice`.

```typescript
const authSlice = createSlice({
  name: "auth",
  initialState,
  reducers: {
    logout(state) {
      state.user = null;
    },
  },
});

export const { logout } = authSlice.actions;
```

Avoid manually creating action types.

Bad:

```typescript
export const LOGOUT = "LOGOUT";
```

---

# Async Logic

## Prefer RTK Query

For API communication use RTK Query before considering thunks.

Good:

```typescript
const usersApi = createApi({
  reducerPath: "usersApi",
  baseQuery: fetchBaseQuery({
    baseUrl: "/api",
  }),
  endpoints: (builder) => ({
    getUsers: builder.query<User[], void>({
      query: () => "/users",
    }),
  }),
});
```

Use RTK Query for:

- Fetching
- Caching
- Re-fetching
- Polling
- Optimistic updates

---

## Use createAsyncThunk Only When Needed

Use `createAsyncThunk` for:

- Complex workflows
- Multi-step processes
- Business logic orchestration

Example:

```typescript
export const login = createAsyncThunk(
  "auth/login",
  async (credentials: LoginRequest) => {
    const response = await api.login(credentials);
    return response.data;
  },
);
```

---

## Handle Async States Explicitly

Every async flow should expose:

```typescript
{
  data: null,
  status: 'idle',
  error: null
}
```

Possible statuses:

```typescript
"idle";
"loading";
"succeeded";
"failed";
```

---

# Selectors

## Never Access State Directly in Components

Bad:

```typescript
const user = useAppSelector((state) => state.auth.user);
```

Preferred:

```typescript
const user = useAppSelector(selectCurrentUser);
```

---

## Create Dedicated Selector Files

```typescript
// authSelectors.ts

export const selectAuthState = (state: RootState) => state.auth;

export const selectCurrentUser = (state: RootState) => state.auth.user;
```

---

## Memoize Expensive Selectors

Use `createSelector`.

```typescript
import { createSelector } from "@reduxjs/toolkit";

export const selectActiveUsers = createSelector([selectUsers], (users) =>
  users.filter((user) => user.active),
);
```

---

# State Design

## Store Only Source of Truth

Store:

```typescript
{
  users: [...]
}
```

Derive:

```typescript
activeUsers;
sortedUsers;
userCount;
```

through selectors.

---

## Avoid Duplicated State

Bad:

```typescript
{
  users: [...],
  activeUsers: [...]
}
```

Good:

```typescript
{
  users: [...]
}
```

---

## Avoid Non-Serializable Values

Never store:

- Date instances
- Functions
- Class instances
- DOM elements
- Promises
- Maps
- Sets

Bad:

```typescript
{
  createdAt: new Date();
}
```

Good:

```typescript
{
  createdAt: "2026-01-01T10:00:00Z";
}
```

---

# RTK Query Standards

## Create a Base API

```typescript
export const baseApi = createApi({
  reducerPath: "api",
  baseQuery: fetchBaseQuery({
    baseUrl: "/api",
  }),
  tagTypes: ["User", "Post"],
  endpoints: () => ({}),
});
```

---

## Inject Endpoints

```typescript
export const usersApi = baseApi.injectEndpoints({
  endpoints: (builder) => ({
    getUsers: builder.query<User[], void>({
      query: () => "/users",
    }),
  }),
});
```

---

## Use Tags for Cache Invalidation

```typescript
getUsers: builder.query({
  query: () => "/users",
  providesTags: ["User"],
});

createUser: builder.mutation({
  query: (body) => ({
    url: "/users",
    method: "POST",
    body,
  }),
  invalidatesTags: ["User"],
});
```

---

# Error Handling

## Standardize Errors

Prefer:

```typescript
{
  message: string;
  code?: string;
}
```

Avoid:

```typescript
any;
unknown;
```

leaking into application code.

---

## Reject With Value

```typescript
return rejectWithValue({
  message: error.message,
});
```

instead of throwing raw errors.

---

# Performance

## Minimize Re-renders

Prefer:

```typescript
const username = useAppSelector(selectUsername);
```

instead of:

```typescript
const auth = useAppSelector(selectAuthState);
```

when only a small piece is needed.

---

## Normalize Large Collections

Use:

```typescript
createEntityAdapter;
```

for:

- Users
- Products
- Messages
- Orders

and any large collection.

---

# Testing

## Test Selectors

```typescript
describe("selectCurrentUser", () => {
  it("returns current user", () => {
    const result = selectCurrentUser(state);
    expect(result).toEqual(user);
  });
});
```

---

## Test Reducers

```typescript
it("should logout", () => {
  const state = reducer(initialState, logout());

  expect(state.user).toBeNull();
});
```

---

## Test Async Thunks

Mock API dependencies and verify:

- pending
- fulfilled
- rejected

states.

